</section><section class="service-faq">

    <div class="tc-container">

        <div class="section-heading">

            <h2>Common Questions</h2>

            <p>
                A few questions people often ask before starting grief counselling.
            </p>

        </div>

        <div class="faq-list">

            <details open>

                <summary>
                    How soon after a loss should I come in?
                </summary>

                <p>

                    Whenever you're ready. Some people reach out in the first
                    few weeks, while others come months or years later when a
                    loss begins to feel heavy again. There isn't a right time.

                </p>

            </details>

            <details>

                <summary>
                    Will I have to talk about exactly what happened?
                </summary>

                <p>

                    Only if you want to. We'll work at your pace, and you never
                    have to share more than feels safe or helpful.

                </p>

            </details>

            <details>

                <summary>
                    I'm grieving a pet. Is that okay to bring here?
                </summary>

                <p>

                    Absolutely. The loss of a beloved animal is real grief and
                    deserves the same care, compassion, and space as any other
                    significant loss.

                </p>

            </details>

            <details>

                <summary>
                    Is walk-and-talk counselling suitable for grief?
                </summary>

                <p>

                    For many people, yes. Walking outdoors can create a gentle,
                    grounding space for difficult emotions. If it feels like a
                    good fit, we can incorporate walk-and-talk sessions into
                    your counselling.

                </p>

            </details>

            <details>

                <summary>
                    Will grief ever completely go away?
                </summary>

                <p>

                    Grief often changes rather than disappears. Counselling
                    isn't about forgetting someone you love—it's about finding
                    a way to carry both your grief and your life forward.

                </p>

            </details>

        </div>

    </div>

</section>
